<p><strong>Ilia Viazov</strong> (1999*) is a composer, sound artist, and performer whose work moves across acoustic composition, electroacoustic performance, live-coding, installation, and DIY instrument-building. His practice is rooted in experimentation ‚Äî exploring the boundaries between composition and performance, and the re-emergence of the instrument as both interface and compositional material. He works with acoustic instruments, self-built objects, embedded hardware, and machine listening, often within systems where the boundary between score, tool, and performer becomes unstable.</p>

<p>Viazov began his musical formation as a bassoon player at the Rostropovich Music College in Voronezh, Russia, before continuing at the Gnesin Russian Academy of Music in Moscow, and then turning to composition at the Tchaikovsky Moscow State Conservatory, where he studied with Vladimir Tarnopolsky and Yuri Kasparov. He continued his studies at the Musikhochschule L√ºbeck, where he is completing a Bachelor in Composition with a focus on Electronic Music and Sound Arts, and works as a student assistant in the Hybrid AI Department at the University of L√ºbeck, where he explores the creative and conceptual implications of machine listening.</p>

<p>He has presented works at Ars Electronica (Linz), Darmst√§dter Ferienkurse, Frequenz Festival (Kiel), +RAIN Festival (Barcelona), and ZKM Karlsruhe, and has participated in festivals including Maerzmusik, Kontakte Festival, Selbstgebaute Musik Festival, and others. His work has received recognition through the Possehlpreis Open Space (1st Prize), the DAAD scholarship, and the L√ºbecker Kompositionswettbewerb.</p>

<p>His output spans acoustic composition, electroacoustic performance, physical sound sculpture, DIY instrument-building, and interactive installation. Alongside his artistic practice, Viazov is active in festival organization in the Kiel/L√ºbeck region and leads workshops in live coding and microcontroller-based instrument design. His work is informed by post-compositional thinking ‚Äî a concern less with fixed scores than with designed systems, emergent process, and the situated body of the performer within technologically extended environments.</p>

